Organisations are guided by the mandate spelt out by the policies and applicable legal framework, the tools for operations that should be used in scanning the horizon, and anticipating any unexpected disruption that would hurt its performance.
Since ancient times, the world community has witnessed many disasters varying in magnitude and severity. Disruptions to business operations could be any unanticipated happening that would slow down the operations, affect performance, lead to business closure and damage the organisation brand.





Risk assessment
Although some organisations have a contingency plan in place to help in critical situations, a majority do not. Most organisations, however, do an inadequate job of managing reputation and brand in case of disruption.
They focus their time and resources on handling a crisis that has already surfaced. This is not risk management; it is crisis management — a knee-jerk reactive approach, whose purpose is to limit the damage, but once done with this, another crisis strikes and the organisation is in a cat-and-mouse race throughout its operational life.
An optimal contingency plan should consider unforeseen factors, their likelihood of happening and their consequences, if they occur to the performance. It should be tested at predetermined intervals, making improvements when and where necessary.



