The severity of any disruption can be measured by its consequences, such as bad reputation, sudden drop in share value, losses in shares, no revenue for the company for specific period and in the worst case, no business at all.
A recovery plan is based on thorough business impact analysis and risk assessment. This involves identification, description and documentation of impact and consequences, implementation of actions to ensure continuity of the operations. Disasters may last for a short or long time, but when an organisation is ready for adversity, it survives and thrives.
The recovery plan can be checked for suitability and applicability by evaluating it against the current scenarios, taking other organisations as examples and simulation of disruption events. As a tool for progressive performance, the documentations of the system must be reviewed at regular intervals.
A good contingency plan allows employees to have enough knowledge on what choices to make, what assets to be protected on high priority and which business operation should continue during a crisis. In other words, organisations have a more controlled procedure to help them come out of a crisis.
International Organisation for Standardisation (ISO) through its Technical Committee ISO/TC 292, security and resilience, in the year 2019 published a standard ISO 22301: 2019 on security and resilience-Business Continuity Management Systems requirements.



